To install critic2, please follow the instructions in:

https://aoterodelaroza.github.io/critic2/installation/

Windows builds
--------------

The Windows GUI package is produced by cross-compiling from Linux with MinGW-w64
and packaging with CPack. The result is a self-contained tree -- shipped both as
a portable .zip and as an NSIS installer .exe -- that bundles every required DLL,
so it runs on a stock Windows machine with no extra dependencies. The steps below
build both packages from scratch.

1. Prerequisites (Debian/Ubuntu package names)

   * MinGW-w64 toolchain, POSIX thread model (required: the win32 thread model
     corrupts memory when the GUI spawns threads):

       apt install gfortran-mingw-w64-x86-64 g++-mingw-w64-x86-64 gcc-mingw-w64-x86-64

     Keep the mingw-w64 runtime in sync with the compiler by using
     "apt full-upgrade", or upgrade the mingw-w64* packages
     explicitly.

   * NSIS, for the installer (provides makensis):

       apt install nsis

   * GLFW 3, Windows 64-bit binaries (GUI only). Download "Windows pre-compiled
     binaries (64-bit)" from https://www.glfw.org/download and unpack it; you
     will point at its include/ and lib-mingw-w64/ directories.

   * (optional) Mesa for Windows, for the software-OpenGL fallback used on
     machines that lack OpenGL 3.3 (old GPUs, Remote Desktop, GPU-less VMs). Get
     a build from https://github.com/pal1000/mesa-dist-win (the MinGW "release"
     package) and use the directory containing opengl32.dll, libgallium_wgl.dll,
     libglapi.dll and dxil.dll. To support Windows 7, use a 24.x release; newer
     Mesa imports Win8+ symbols and will not load there.

   * (optional) OpenBLAS, for fast external LAPACK/BLAS. A prebuilt MinGW
     Windows build is available from https://github.com/OpenMathLib/OpenBLAS
     (the "OpenBLAS-<version>-x64.zip" asset). Without it critic2 falls back to
     its slower bundled reference LAPACK.

   * (optional) FreeType, for higher-quality GUI font rendering. It has no
     MinGW-compatible prebuilt binary, but imgui needs only its core API, so a
     minimal (dependency-free) DLL is easily cross-built from the source at
     https://download.savannah.gnu.org/releases/freetype/. Without it the GUI
     uses its lower-quality built-in font rasterizer.

   * (optional) readline, for interactive command-line editing and history.
     GNU readline needs termcap/termios and does not build for Windows; the
     substitute is wineditline (https://sourceforge.net/projects/mingweditline/),
     a BSD-licensed, readline-API-compatible library whose edit.dll exports the
     readline/add_history/read_history/write_history functions critic2 uses.
     Without it the CLI falls back to the plain Windows console line editor.

   These downloads can be automated: run

       tools/fetch-windows-deps.sh [DEST]      # needs curl, unzip, p7zip-full

   which fetches GLFW, Mesa and OpenBLAS and cross-builds a minimal FreeType and
   a readline-compatible wineditline into DEST (default ./windows-deps), then
   prints a ready-to-paste recipe (the configure line with all the -D options
   filled in, plus the build and package commands) that you can run directly
   instead of assembling the flags below by hand. Set FETCH_MESA=0,
   FETCH_LAPACK=0, FETCH_FREETYPE=0 or FETCH_READLINE=0 to skip a dependency, or
   GLFW_VERSION / MESA_VERSION / OPENBLAS_VERSION / FREETYPE_VERSION /
   WINEDITLINE_VERSION to pick versions. (The FreeType and readline cross-builds
   need the MinGW toolchain and cmake; each is skipped with a warning if either
   is absent.)

   The remaining optional libraries critic2 can use (libxc, HDF5, nlopt,
   libcint, tblite) have no MinGW-compatible prebuilt Windows binaries; enabling
   them means cross-building each from source first, so the recipe below leaves
   them off. OpenMP needs no download -- it is provided by the toolchain's
   libgomp -- and is enabled below.

2. Configure (Release, GUI, with the software fallback, fast BLAS and OpenMP).
   If you used fetch-windows-deps.sh, it already printed this command with the
   paths filled in; otherwise set them yourself:

     GLFW=/path/to/glfw-3.4.bin.WIN64
     MESA=/path/to/mesa-dist-win/x64          # optional
     OPENBLAS=/path/to/openblas-x64           # optional (contains bin/ lib/ include/)
     FREETYPE=/path/to/freetype-mingw         # optional (contains bin/ lib/ include/)
     READLINE=/path/to/wineditline-mingw      # optional (contains bin/ lib/ include/)

     cmake -S . -B build-win \
       -DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE=cmake/toolchains/x86_64-w64-mingw32.cmake \
       -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release \
       -DENABLE_GUI=ON -DENABLE_OPENMP=ON \
       -DGLFW3_INCLUDE_DIR=$GLFW/include \
       -DGLFW3_LIBRARY=$GLFW/lib-mingw-w64/libglfw3dll.a \
       -DMESA_DIR=$MESA \
       -DUSE_EXTERNAL_LAPACK=ON -DBLA_VENDOR=OpenBLAS \
       -DUSE_FREETYPE=ON -DUSE_READLINE=ON \
       -DCRITIC2_FIND_ROOT="$OPENBLAS;$FREETYPE;$READLINE" \
       -DUSE_LIBXC=OFF -DUSE_HDF5=OFF \
       -DUSE_NLOPT=OFF -DUSE_LIBCINT=OFF -DUSE_TBLITE=OFF

   Notes:
   * Drop -DMESA_DIR to omit the software fallback (the GUI then needs the target
     machine to provide OpenGL 3.3 itself).
   * For a command-line-only package use -DENABLE_GUI=OFF and omit the GLFW,
     MESA and FREETYPE options.
   * -DGLFW3_ROOT=$GLFW also works when the layout is standard; the explicit
     INCLUDE_DIR/LIBRARY above is reliable for the glfw.org WIN64 binary dist,
     whose import library lives in lib-mingw-w64/. Use libglfw3dll.a (not
     libglfw3.a) so glfw3.dll is bundled.
   * -DCRITIC2_FIND_ROOT is a ';'-separated list of extra prefixes added to the
     cross find-root; each is searched for import libraries (<prefix>/lib) and
     bundled DLLs (<prefix>/bin). It carries both OpenBLAS and FreeType here.
   * External LAPACK: -DBLA_VENDOR=OpenBLAS tells CMake's FindLAPACK to use the
     OpenBLAS in CRITIC2_FIND_ROOT. To skip it and use critic2's bundled
     reference LAPACK instead, drop it and set -DUSE_EXTERNAL_LAPACK=OFF.
   * FreeType improves GUI font rendering; drop -DUSE_FREETYPE=ON (or its
     find-root entry) to fall back to imgui's built-in rasterizer.
   * readline: the wineditline prefix built by fetch-windows-deps.sh is laid out
     as a readline-compatible tree (lib/libreadline.dll.a, include/readline/) so
     the stock FindREADLINE locates it; drop -DUSE_READLINE=ON to use the plain
     console line editor instead.
   * The other optional libraries (libxc, HDF5, nlopt, libcint, tblite) are off
     because they have no MinGW prebuilt binaries; each can be enabled if you
     cross-build it and add its prefix to -DCRITIC2_FIND_ROOT (or use the
     library's own -D options). Each adds bundled DLLs.
   * See the header of cmake/toolchains/x86_64-w64-mingw32.cmake for more.

3. Build

     cmake --build build-win -j

   This produces build-win/src/critic2.exe (console CLI) and, for a GUI build,
   build-win/src/critic2-gui.exe (windowed GUI).

4. Package. Run CPack from the build directory. All required runtime DLLs (the
   compiler runtime, GLFW, and OpenBLAS/FreeType/readline if used) are detected
   and bundled automatically.

     cd build-win
     cpack -G ZIP     # portable  -> critic2-<version>-win64.zip
     cpack -G NSIS    # installer -> critic2-<version>-win64.exe

   or produce both at once (also what a bare "cpack" does here when makensis is
   present):

     cpack -G "ZIP;NSIS"

   Package layout: bin/ holds the executables (native OpenGL) with their runtime
   DLLs; if MESA_DIR was set, a sibling bin-mesa/ holds a second GUI executable
   next to Mesa's software OpenGL (it shares bin/'s runtime DLLs, so they are not
   duplicated). The root has small launcher executables -- double-clickable, with
   the critic2 icon and no console flash -- that run the right binary relative to
   their own location (so they work wherever the package is unpacked):

     critic2.exe                        the GUI (native OpenGL)
     critic2 (console).exe              the command line
     critic2 (software rendering).exe   the GUI forced onto Mesa/llvmpipe, for
                                        machines with no GPU or OpenGL < 3.3

   The .zip is portable: unzip it anywhere and double-click a launcher; critic2
   finds its data next to the executables, with no environment variables. The
   .exe installer puts critic2 under Program Files, adds bin to PATH, and creates
   Start-Menu and desktop shortcuts.

Native build in an MSYS2 shell (no toolchain file needed):

    cmake -B build -G "MSYS Makefiles" [-DENABLE_GUI=ON ...]
    cmake --build build -j

The regression tests are POSIX-only and are skipped on Windows.
